Biomass hauls” are defined as positive performance survey trawl hauls (i.e., haul performance considered to be acceptable) from an Alaska Fisheries Science Center bottom trawl survey time-series for which a sampling design, gear type, accessory type, tow duration and survey methodology are standardized such that the distance fished and average net spread from those hauls can be used to calculate an area swept for standardizing catch sample weights and numbers by survey year and by taxon or taxonomic group in terms of Catch per Unit Effort (CPUE).  CPUE’s are used to derive estimates of biomass, population size, abundance-at-length and abundance-at-age that can be used to index or monitor trends in marine life populations over the span of the respective survey time-series for purposes of stock assessment, ecosystem monitoring or other research.

Taxon Code. The species code of the organism associated with the "common_name" and "scientific_name" columns. For a complete species list, review the [code books](https://www.fisheries.noaa.gov/resource/document/groundfish-survey-species-code-manual-and-data-codes-ma

Taxon Confidence Rating. Confidence in the ability of the survey team to correctly identify the taxon to the specified level, based solely on identification skill (e.g., not likelihood of a taxon being caught at that station on a location-by-location basis). Quality codes follow:

Taxon Confidence Rating. Confidence in the ability of the survey team to correctly identify the taxon to the specified level, based solely on identification skill (e.g., not likelihood of a taxon being caught at that station on a location-by-location basis). Quality codes follow: **"High"**: High confidence and consistency. Taxonomy is stable and reliable at this level, and field identification characteristics are well known and reliable. **"Moderate"**: Moderate confidence. Taxonomy may be questionable at this level, or field identification characteristics may be variable and difficult to assess consistently. **"Low"**: Low confidence. Taxonomy is incompletely known, or reliable field identification characteristics are unknown. Documentation: [Species identification confidence in the eastern Bering Sea shelf survey (1982-2008)](http://apps-afsc.fisheries.noaa.gov/Publications/ProcRpt/PR2009-04.pdf), [Species identification confidence in the eastern Bering Sea slope survey (1976-2010)](http://apps-afsc.fisheries.noaa.gov/Publications/ProcRpt/PR2014-05.pdf), and [Species identification confidence in the Gulf of Alaska and Aleutian Islands surveys (1980-2011)](http://apps-afsc.fisheries.noaa.gov/Publications/ProcRpt/PR2014-01.pdf).
